<paragraph id="139FBE9CA117F1DDFB14C4E4E6233EFD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">In designating a lectotype, we have chosen the only original specimen at Paris with a corolla.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6CB3FAF64B5CF358ACF15932675B194B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="9FE2B24276705B66A2BE0981510C37A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F0762C15FFE33953782BBD218596D25" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A coastal species resembling 
<taxonomicName id="1AF2A2ABA1F044B665B837CF04A4058C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jalapa">
<emphasis id="DEE0BA17F9521F007CD31A8ADBB5B40E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea jalapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differing in the more hirsute, usually 3-lobed leaves and white, usually solitary flowers as well as the distinctive habitat. It is reported to be a night-flowering moth pollinated species (Austin and 
<normalizedToken id="BE6D64D3F6C0DC79BA4748B72E1D3071" originalValue="Huáman">Huaman</normalizedToken>
1996).
</paragraph>
